Comment:
With this move I begin to contend for the center and oppose your pawns. There are several primary responses frequently played: The main line is 3.Nc3. Black can continue with the following variations:

Rubinstein Variation 3...dxe4;
Winawer Variation 3...Bb4;
Classical Variation 3...Nf6;

***********************************************************************
If White chooses not to play 3.Nc3 he can instead play the Exchange Variation: 3.exd5 exd5; the Advance Variation 3.e5; the Tarrasch Variation 3.Nd2.

The Advance Variation is the most aggressive, blocking in Black's LSB. Black then starts an assault on the pawns via c5 and possibly (after more preparation), f6.
